'''Roy Dotrice''', OBE, (born 26 May 1923) is a British actor. He fought in [[wikipedia:World War II|World War II]] as part of the [[wikipedia:Royal Air Force|Royal Air Force]] and spent four years in a German prisoner of war camp. He began acting upon his return to England and is a fifty year veteran of the stage and screen. He achieved critical success as [[wikipedia:John Aubrey|John Aubrey]] in the one-man play ''[[wikipedia:Brief Lives|Brief Lives]]'', beginning in 1965. Dotrice played the role in 1,782 performances over several decades, earning him a place in the [[wikipedia:Guinness Book of Records|Guinness Book of Records]] for the greatest number of solo performances by an actor in a play. He also achieved critical acclaim for his portrayal of [[wikipedia:Leopold Mozart|Leopold Mozart]], the father of [[wikipedia:Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart|Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart]], in the high-acclaimed and successful 1984 movie ''[[wikipedia:Amadeus (film)|Amadeus]]''. He was made a [[wikipedia:Officer of the Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] in the 2008 Honours List.

Dotrice began a long-running relationship with the science fiction and fantasy genre by playing the role of Commissioner Simmons in two episodes of ''[[wikipedia:Space 1999|Space 1999]]'' in 1975. He would go on to appear in genre and near-genre shows such as ''[[wikipedia:Picket Fences|Picket Fences]]'', ''[[wikipedia:Sliders|Sliders]]'', ''[[wikipedia:Angel (TV series)|Angel]]'', ''[[wikipedia:Babylon 5|Babylon 5]]'' and ''[[wikipedia:Hercules:The Legendary Journeys|Hercules:The Legendary Journeys]]''. He played Zeus on ''Hercules: The Legendary Journies'' and Wesley's father on ''Angel''. His most recent major genre role was as King Balor in the 2008 film ''[[wikipedia:Hellboy II: The Golden Army|Hellboy II: The Golden Army]]'', where all of his dialogue was in [[wikipedia:Gaelic|Gaelic]].

Dotrice first met [[George R.R. Martin]] while they were both working on the 1988 TV series ''[[wikipedia:Beauty and the Beast (TV series)|Beauty and the Beast]]''. Dotrice played the role of Father, the leader of an underground community, while Martin worked on the show as a writer, script-editor and producer. They became friends and ''Beauty and the Beast'' was the last television production that author Martin worked on before turning his attention to writing the ''A Song of Ice and Fire'' book series. Martin later asked Dotrice to read the [[wikipedia:audiobook|audiobook]] editions of the novels. Dotrice originally read the first three and the fifth books in the series, as he was unable to work on the fourth due to time commitments. However, in response to huge demand from fans, a Dotrice-narrated recording of the fourth book was released in late 2011, shortly after the fifth book. Dotrice is thus the actor most familiar with the source material for ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' upon his casting. His role in reading the audiobooks has since earned him a second Guinness World Record, this time for the largest number of characters voiced in an audiobook.

In the series Dotrice was originally hired to play Grand Maester [[Pycelle]]. George R.R. Martin confirmed his casting on 23 June 2010. Unfortunately, Dotrice suffered from health problems which necessitated a four-month convalescent period, just before production was due to begin. As a result Dotrice had to withdraw from the series and was replaced by [[Julian Glover]], a former colleague of his from a previous project.&lt;ref&gt;[http://grrm.livejournal.com/168109.html George R.R. Martin's blog] explaining Pycelle's recasting&lt;/ref&gt; Martin and the production team were hopeful of finding another role for Dotrice to play, and on 7 August 2011 Martin confirmed that Dotrice would be playing the role of [[Hallyne]] in the [[Season 2|second season]] instead.&lt;ref&gt;[http://grrm.livejournal.com/231396.html?thread=14435300#t14435300 George R.R. Martin's blog]&lt;/ref&gt; He joined the cast as a guest star in &quot;[[The Ghost of Harrenhal]].&quot;
